<subSubSection id="0FCC6525FF9BFFE5FF2154AAFC38A325" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="476936AEFF9BFFE5FF2154AAFC38A325" blockId="1.[151,1437,685,1108]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">
<emphasis id="75A2EABCFF9BFFE5FF2154AAFECDA2D1" bold="true" box="[151,274,685,711]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
According to the identification key proposed by 
<bibRefCitation id="23474B5FFF9BFFE5FC8654A9FC36A2D1" author="Logunov, D. V." box="[816,1001,685,712]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" pagination="233 - 263" refId="ref9649" refString="Logunov, D. V. (2010) On new central Asian genus and species of wolf spiders (Araneae: Lycosidae) exhibiting a pronounced sexual size dimorphism. Proceedings of the Zoological Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences, 314 (3), 233 - 263." type="journal article" year="2010">Logunov (2010)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="80D64D2DFF9BFFE5FC4554A9FB9EA2D1" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1804" box="[1011,1089,686,711]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Lycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75A2EABCFF9BFFE5FC4554A9FB9EA2D1" box="[1011,1089,686,711]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Lycosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other large central Asian burrowing wolf spiders in the following characters: (1) hooked-shaped median apophysis; (2) singular synembolus; (3) epigyne comprising an anterior elevation (4) absence of epigynal depression, (5) distinct septal pedicle; (4) relatively complex spermathecae with long and S-shaped ducts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0FCC6525FF9BFFE5FF71553AFD72A445" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="476936AEFF9BFFE5FF71553AFD72A445" blockId="1.[151,1437,685,1108]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">
<emphasis id="75A2EABCFF9BFFE5FF71553AFE90A341" bold="true" box="[199,335,829,855]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Comments.</emphasis>
Spiders of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="80D64D2DFF9BFFE5FDE75539FD40A341" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1804" box="[593,671,830,855]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Lycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75A2EABCFF9BFFE5FDE75539FD40A341" box="[593,671,830,855]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Lycosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are relatively large and fossorial. The genus includes 224 species distributed worldwide, with the highest species diversity in Asia and South America (
<bibRefCitation id="23474B5FFF9BFFE5FBE05566FA4EA36D" author="World Spider Catalog" box="[1110,1425,865,891]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" refId="ref10125" refString="World Spider Catalog (2022) World Spider Catalog. Version 23.0. Natural History Museum Bern. Available from: http: // wsc. nmbe. ch (accessed 21 February 2022) https: // doi. org / 10.24436 / 2" type="book" year="2022">World Spider Catalog 2022</bibRefCitation>
). Five species have been recorded from 
<collectingCountry id="3FC1763EFF9BFFE5FDF85581FDA1A3B6" box="[590,638,902,928]" name="Iran" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Iran</collectingCountry>
, including two endemic species (
<taxonomicName id="80D64D2DFF9BFFE5FC4F5581FA43A389" authority="Nadolny &amp; Zamani, 2017" authorityName="Nadolny &amp; Zamani" authorityYear="2017" box="[1017,1436,901,927]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Lycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aragogi">
<emphasis id="75A2EABCFF9BFFE5FC4F5581FBAFA389" box="[1017,1136,902,927]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">L. aragogi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="23474B5FFF9BFFE5FBCE5582FA43A389" author="Nadolny, A. A. &amp; Zamani, A." box="[1144,1436,901,927]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" pagination="597 - 600" refId="ref9813" refString="Nadolny, A. A. &amp; Zamani, A. (2017) A new species of burrowing wolf spiders (Araneae: Lycosidae: Lycosa) from Iran. Zootaxa, 4286 (4), 597 - 600. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zotaxa / 4286.4.13" type="journal article" year="2017">Nadolny &amp; Zamani, 2017</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="80D64D2DFF9BFFE5FF7155ADFD1BA3D5" authority="Nadolny &amp; Zamani, 2020" authorityName="Nadolny &amp; Zamani" authorityYear="2020" box="[199,708,937,963]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Lycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrophthalma">
<emphasis id="75A2EABCFF9BFFE5FF7155ADFE49A3D5" box="[199,406,937,963]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">L. macrophthalma</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="23474B5FFF9BFFE5FE2855AEFD1BA3D5" author="Nadolny, A. A. &amp; Zamani, A." box="[414,708,937,963]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" pagination="205 - 212" refId="ref9867" refString="Nadolny, A. A. &amp; Zamani, A. (2020) A new species of wolf spiders of the genus Lycosa (Aranei: Lycosidae) from Iran. Zoosystematica Rossica, 29 (2), 205 - 212. https: // doi. org / 10.31610 / zsr / 2020.29.2.205" type="journal article" year="2020">Nadolny &amp; Zamani, 2020</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
), which were described from the females (
<bibRefCitation id="23474B5FFF9BFFE5FB1355AEFF0EA3F1" author="World Spider Catalog" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" refId="ref10125" refString="World Spider Catalog (2022) World Spider Catalog. Version 23.0. Natural History Museum Bern. Available from: http: // wsc. nmbe. ch (accessed 21 February 2022) https: // doi. org / 10.24436 / 2" type="book" year="2022">World Spider Catalog 2022</bibRefCitation>
) and hence can be compared to the new species being described in the present paper based on the similarities in copulatory organs (see 
<taxonomicName id="80D64D2DFF9BFFE5FE0255F5FDBCA41D" authority="Shafaie &amp; Nadolny &amp; Mirshamsi, 2022" authorityName="Shafaie &amp; Nadolny &amp; Mirshamsi" authorityYear="2022" box="[436,611,1009,1035]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Lycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="soboutii" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="75A2EABCFF9BFFE5FE0255F5FDBCA41D" box="[436,611,1009,1035]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Lycosa soboutii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="75A2EABCFF9BFFE5FDDF55F6FD77A41D" bold="true" box="[617,680,1009,1035]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6E9157C7FF9BFFE5FDDF55F6FD77A41D" box="[617,680,1009,1035]" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
). Also, the new species is assigned to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="80D64D2DFF9BFFE5FB0B55F5FAD4A41D" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1804" box="[1213,1291,1010,1035]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Lycosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75A2EABCFF9BFFE5FB0B55F5FAD4A41D" box="[1213,1291,1010,1035]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="502">Lycosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
according to the similarities of habitus and epigyne: large spiders with septal pedicle, massive folds at vulva, not anchor-shaped septum and the absence of epigynal depression.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
